description:
On March 15, 2014, two Dutch students boarded a plane from Amsterdam to Costa Rica. Like any recent graduate,  21 year old Kris Kremers and 22  year old Lisanne Froon were excited students ready to see the world after graduation. After going on a short hike on the Pianista trail, they were never seen again.

Credits (music, sources, etc.): https://pastebin.com/PcM6eK1y
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/unpred.ictable/
Donate: https://ko-fi.com/unpredictable

comments.text:
A couple things to clarify:
1) The backpack was actually originally found dirty and wet, with the investigators waiting for the electronics to dry before searching them. The claim that it was found clean seems to stem from a misinterpreted article.
2) People have recreated the same camera model skipping a photo number by deleting it directly on the camera, by having it fall, or having it sustain water damage.

I think they either got lost or slipped and got injured or somehow immobilized. The "suspicious" stuff actually convinces me that foul play didn't happen. Manually deleting photos, faking 112 calls, scattering body parts in the jungle, etc. Seems like an insane amount of effort and risk when it would be much easier and safer to make sure that bag and those bodies were never found.

comments.text:
After watching The island with bear grylls which coincidentally was filmed in panama I think the most logical explanation is that they got lost. If you Google el mirador del pianista boquete panam you can find multiple traveler photos of the trail. At the time they went on the trail there werent any signs or markers to indicate that the trail had ended. The girls didnt speak Spanish and they werent from the area. The trail doesnt have signs or a post that indicate which way back to town. After exploring beyond the mirador for close to 3 hours, the girls panicked when they realized they were going in circles and it was getting dark soon. 

The jungle is pitch dark and there are tons of predators which include snakes, spiders, jaguars, cougars, coyotes. Plus reports at the time indicated that rain had slowed down the rescue efforts. My best guess is they tried to climb to high ground in order to get a cellular signal. 

The night pictures showed what appears to look like S.O.S sign with white paper. The camera appears to have been used as a flashlight as there was proof of pictures taken with flash every 9 seconds standing in the same spot. The night pictures also indicate they were on high ground overlooking a steep drop below. 

At some point it appears they tried to follow the culebra river until they reached a town. Unfortunately the culebra river runs to the Caribbean side which would take them farther away from boquete. 

I dont believe that they were killed by a gang of local boys that followed them into the jungle because it would be easier to dig a grave and bury the girls and all their belongings and ensure they vanished without a trace instead of turning phone off and on 77 times on several days and taking 100s of photos in order to make it appear the girls were lost in the jungle. Lastly, it doesnt make sense to fold all the girls belongings and put camera in waterproof bag so that someone can find it later.
comments.author: @Mike12361O

comments.text:
Once, hiking with my friend, we got lost in a snowstorm and completely missed our turn. After climbing a couple of hours in a wrong direction, knee deep in snow and zero visibility - we realized that something is odd, as we had not met any person on the trail. 
What did we do? We traced our steps back, gradually returning to the original junction. Even though, we had an idea just to climb a hill and watch from there where to go.
The point is - the simplest ideas are usually the safest. Take your time to understand the situation you are in, consider the options and decide if your life is at risk.
+ always leave a not to someone where do you go and when you are expecting to be back
comments.author: @Sh.I16

comments.text:
I get the feeling that the people that like to believe they were followed etc. are those that either love making up drama or have never been in a dense wood/jungle. The kidnapper / killer theory makes no sense because in that terrain they could have easily done the crime and left no trace whatsoever. 

Jungles are intimidating places, it is impossible to really understand how thick and hostile they can be unless you've been in one. I've been to many jungle areas in Asia and one of the key features is that mobile phone signal is lost very quickly even in national parks with main roads nearby. Even in the "clearings", it is still difficult to get a signal.

Another issue is that it is soo easy to get disorientated, overheated (even suffer heat stroke) and become panicked. You can also  lose track of people who were only a few metres in front of you and not be able to hear them.

To me it really seems like these girls just sadly overestimated their ability, thought they would do "just an extra little bit" and got into trouble. This is a much more common cause of death than a random psychopath. 
Even the backpack disappearing / reappearing could indicate someone found it and moved it to a more obvious spot (to be helpful) or didn't realise it wasn't just lost, or maybe it was moved by an animal.

comments.text: I was born in Panam. I have done that same trail more than 11 times over for fun.  The first couple of times I did it on my own, the rest accompanied by friends. I can confirm that it would require an insane amount of wilfull intention to get lost along such a well-signaled trail. Once we ended up returning after sunset because of having ventured further beyond the conventional turning-back point. To put it simply, you must be spelled down by some kind of sudden condition affecting your awareness and sense of orientation in order to get drawn far enough into the wilderness and not be able to find your way back. This trail is not in the Darin area, where getting lost is an actual plausibility. While I do not think it reasonable to indulge in witch-hunting or scape-goating to account for hurt public sensitivities, I am fully aware of the characteristic lack of professionalism from panamanian authorities and more shockingly, of the extent to which twisted individuals belonging to gangs, heavily invested in drugs and nefarious activities are capable to go. Rapes are sadly not uncommon in this country, women don't generally feel their dignity safe while walking alone among men in public ways, even during the day, and heinous crimes have been perpetrated in recent times. Poverty, cultural decay and the ignorance bred by it all can twist individuals' worldview. I am far from dramatically claiming these things are the norm here, yet it would take an extreme measure of empty national pride to deny that such things do happen here. Some years ago, some norwegian tourists got assaulted in their own boat off the coast of Coln province (a province with a dual personality: on the one side, a beacon of historical tourism, and on the other side one of the most notoriously criminals-infested areas in Panam) by criminals who raped a girl in front of her boyfriend and robbed them. Again, don't underestimate the level of savagery that ignorance and cultural decay can breed in a population. I am not the gloomy and boring "don't trust anyone" kind of guy, and I trust in human potential and virtue, but acknowledgment of reality is also necessary to approach issues of any kind.

This seems fairly simple to me. First, the girls (being Dutch) weren't used to this sort of landscape. They went on the hike and either didn't know to turn back or they decided to purposefully continue on. There are reported smaller trails just used by locals that connect to the one they were on. I suspect they decided to continue. Then, they walked for three hours, getting lost as they started to lose the path. Then, Kris falls in some way. I suspect it was on a river bank as they were trying to follow the river bed. She has a major injury (likely the broken pelvis) and potentially a blow to the back of her head (showing her hair in the one photo and it looks like at the very bottom potentially a blow) and this is when they start calling 112 (emergency services for Dutch). This is them calling because it wouldn't be the number someone else tries in this region. Then, they try multiple times calling 112 and 911 over the next couple of days. Dense jungle prevents them from getting through. Lisa's phone dies first even though they attempt to save the batteries. Meanwhile, Kris is really hurt and in a lot of pain. The majority of calling is done by Lisa from her phone. Unfortunately, Kris dies sometime on April 3rd or 4th. Lisa's phone has no battery left after the 4th. She starts trying to use Kris's phone, but doesn't have the pin code. She tries entering multiple pins she thinks Kris might have used. Kris was badly hurt and never got to tell her the pin. Perhaps even...if she did have a head blow...wasn't fully coherent. So that is why there are multiple attempts with the wrong pin. Then I think it's likely Lisa tries to walk out after Kris dies...knowing it is her only hope. She might have even tried to walk to high ground to attempt to get a cell phone signal. At one point, she uses the camera flash for lighting and that's why we see odd pictures. Unfortunately, on April 11th, Lisa dies. She turned on Kris's iPhone and had it on for an hour attempting to find signal. She probably hoped she could make an emergency call even without the pin. But, she turns it off after an hour with 22% battery remaining. She never turns it on again, suggesting she doesn't make it another night. Likely she was either injured or died from exposure/thirst/hunger. If not, with 22% left she likely would have tried again. 

The foul play idea is ridiculous. What captors would let them keep their cell phones? And what captors would be smart enough to try 112 or 911 instead of the local emergency numbers? Also, why even bother trying to fake anything? 

They found the backpack and bones spread out because Lisa kept going...trying to find a way out. Kris had already died and she didn't know what to do.

Camera's memory card would use NAND flash, and the data woulda been stored as JPEGs. Wear levelling algorithms on the filesystem driver mean that it's highly unlikely the data of the photo 509 was overwritten by data from subsequent photos. Because of how the JPEG algorithm works (DCT --> compression), it's decently resilient to corruption. DCT transform offers some redundancy in case certain harmonics in the cosine sequence are lost, and compression makes it less likely that critical data was overwritten due to smaller size.

Two things make the deletion of image 509 particularly spooky to me:
1) I personally could probably recover IMG_509.
2) Notice that IMG_509 was taken between the last remarkably 'happy' photo taken by the girls, and photos of the wilderness at night... If that's not spooky, I dunno what is.

comments.text:
This video should not be so quick to wildly speculate about foul play. There is simply no evidence of it. The "incorrect pin attempts" (if that happened at all) could be the result of Lisanne trying desperately to guess Kris's pin OR it could be the result of the effects of exposure and starvation. (Note: other human beings in similar circumstances have been known to get simple things wrong, such as writing the wrong date in their journal.) It's also unclear if they were trying to unlock the phone and putting in wrong numbers or simply checking the signal!

Secondly, if they eventually fell and/or drowned in a river, their bodies would rapidly start to decompose which in the right conditions can cause the body to break apart. It's very common for the feet of people who drown in rivers or other moving water to detach from the body cleanly at the ankle. The Salish Sea human foot discoveries are perfect examples of this - from Wikipedia, "Decomposition may separate the foot from the body because the ankle is relatively weak, while buoyancy caused by air either inside or trapped within a shoe would allow it to float away. The B.C. Coroners Service never found cut marks on any bones that suggest the feet were severed from the bodies." Lisanne's foot found detached in this way doesn't raise more questions; it clearly answers the question of where her body was when it began to decompose - the river.

Thirdly, the DNA found on the bag could have found its way onto the bag at any point leading up to hike, and it is very reasonable to assume that it would be difficult to get any meaningful DNA from such an item (which wasn't clean when it was found; that's simply incorrect). We know, for example as per this video, that they were volunteering at a school. That DNA could have been from any number of adults or children who came into contact with them leading up to this day.

Fourthly, what evidence is there that the bleaching was unnatural? What evidence is there to prove it would have taken too long naturally in this area in this time of year? To what extent is the bone bleached? The fact the bleaching is discussed at such a high level indicates this script was written by someone without the right expertise or willingness to seek it out.

Fifthly, the picture of the hair is over exposed, that is all, just like most of the other photos shared in this video.

Finally (god so many things...), in what universe do you need a computer to delete a single photo on a digital camera? Perhaps the woman taking the photos was simply upset at the photo they took. Maybe the other woman was dead or unwell and the photographer didn't want to see the photo anymore. It could have been any reason. OR it was simply a damaged SD card from water exposure.

So many people wanting to find a murderer in this small place when the story is about the locals doing what they could to find these women alive.
